The following was taken directly from my birding notes for this date and location: --Was actually assisting with tagging of oak trees that were marked for impact associated with the "Eastern Trwnsportation Corridor" (which later became the SR-241 toll road). Was with two others (non-birders, Ann Pietro and Mike Amlimg), and we were doing work in both the upper Gypsum Canyon and Blind Canyon watersheds on this date. ----Regarding the Time entered: time segments were actually not separated out between what was spent in upper Gypsum and what was spent in Blind Canyon (but roughly only a half of the time indicated was actually spent in Gypsum).  It was apparent from my notes that we spent the morning in upper Gypsum.    Weather:  60 (deg F) to low 70s. Low clouds and fog during the AM. Habitat:  CSS, chaparral (Chamise dominated), and coast live oak woodland. Oaks mainly isolated patches of narrow oak riparian, except for a nice grove of mature trees way up the north-facing slope of upper Gypsum.
SPECIES COMMENTS: One over Windy Ridge (the divide between the Gypsum and Blind canyon watersheds. Later in the day, near the mouth of Blind Canyon, an Osprey was seen harassing an adult GOLDEN EAGLE.

With Mike San Miguel, Bruce Broadbooks.  Pectoral Sandpiper: "a;png w. shore of southernmost pond, then flew w/ dowitcher. Well-studied w/ scopes, first picked out by NBB. Fine breast streaks, suggesting female. Legs greenish-yellow. A large Calidris w/ fairly long wings, slightly curved, rather long (but stout) bill. Lots of dark centers on back/scaps/coverts. Typical Pectoral pattern of breast streaks cut off sharply from white belly. rare here in spring."
